subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Males of 

X. lemniscatus

can be recognized by their palps with the very long, heavily sclerotized apophysis, the laterally pointing bump and the slightly twisted membranous outgrowth on the bulb (
Figs 13H
; 
14A–E
). Females are distinguished by the epigastric area consisting of a triangle-shaped, strongly protruding structure with a median stripe (
Figs 15B,E
; 
16A–D
).
